<br>
The reason is simple:  Yes, the &quot;rule of thumb&quot; says you'll be doubling your money so that you have 2 18s and can lose to the dealer's 19.  However, statistically, it is *FAR* in your advantage to do this... without going into the math, safe to say that 18 is a statistically &quot;winning hand&quot; - in other words, with an 18, even with a dealer 9 showing, you will win more often than you lose.<br>
<br>
There is exactly ONE reason why the casino makes money on Blackjack.  They go last.  Gives all the people who WOULD have beaten them a chance to bust, first.<br>
<br>
Always split aces and 8s... aces because 2 21s &gt; 1 12, and 8s because 18 is a winning hand and 16 is a losing hand.  Don't even look at the dealer's card unless you're counting.<br>
<br>
Never take insurance unless you're counting (and if you know how to count, you know when to take insurance :) )<br>
<br>
Craps has better odds than blackjack but only if you only play the line :)  Blackjack is the only game in the casino that you *can* make money on, though - but you have to count cards to do it.  This is perfectly legal in Atlantic City but will get you booted in Vegas :) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uyawgmothdaemon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>YawgmothDaemon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>n00b</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/30/01 5:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm34.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> standing and 16 is just dumb</span><hr size=1> standing at 16 with the house showing a 9 is just dumb =P<br>
